ur, and Fundamentalism in Canada -- tPart Five. Matters of State: Redefining the Sacred in Public Life, 1960-2000 -- t12. Catholicism's 'Quiet Revolution': Maintenant and the New Public Catholicism in Quebec after 1960 -- t13. The Christian Recessional in Ontario's Public Schools -- t14. From a Private to a Public Religion: The History of the Public Service Christian Fellowship -- tPart Six. Bearing Witness: The Voice of Religious Outsiders in Public Life -- t15. 'Justice and Only Justice Thou Shalt Pursue': Considerations on the Social Voice of Canada's Reform Rabbis -- t16. Canadian Mennonites and a Widening World -- t17. Sikhism and Secular Authority -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcademic and popular opinions agree that Canadian public life has become wholly secularized during the last hundred years. As this book acknowledges, religion has indeed lost most of its influence in education, politics and various interest groups. But this rigorously researched volume argues that religion was one of the early institutional bases of the public sphere, and although it has since become differentiated from the state, it should not be overlooked or underestimated by historians and sociologists of modern Canada. A compilation of scholarly case studies, it addresses the continuing influence of religion on modern, 'secular' institutions and thus on shaping communal identities.Van Die's book brings together some of Canada's leading historians of religion - including an entry by distinguished US historian, Mark Noll. Religion and Public Life in Canada shows an awareness of the effects of issues such as gender, ethnicity, and regionalism, and considers the recent influence of previously 'outsider' religions such as Judaism and Sikhism. By challenging the assumption that religion has become a matter only of private concern, and by showing its historical and continued relevance to public life, the book takes the debate over secularization on to an entirely new plane of concern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity and politicszCanada. 0aReligion and politicszCanada. 0aReligion and statezCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aAcheson, T.W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAustin, Alvyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Sharon Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGidney, R.D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJantz, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinnear, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillar, W.P.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, J.R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoll, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPage, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerin, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeljak, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStebner, Eleanor J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTulchinsky, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Die, Marguerite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Die, Marguerite, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/v